2.3. Partial least squares regression (PLSR)
Partial least squares regression modeling provide a kind of manylinear regression modeling method. The measurable matrix is highly correlated with large dimension, OLSR might be no longer valid. To solve this problem, the PLSR has been proposed. PLSR focused on principal component analysis, canonical correlation analysis and linear regression analysis features. So, in addition to providing a more reasonable regression model in the analysis results, PLSR [23] can complete some researches similar to principal component analysis and canonical correlation analysis. PLSR is widely used in many ﬁelds, such as fault detection [24], neuroimaging [25], monitoring on modern industry [26] and analysis of rail freight. Many improvements have been made in PLS since 1982 when Herman Wold proposed the PLS algorithm [27,28]. In this section, the standard PLSR method will be considered as follows.

 Step 3: Count the regression coefﬁcient matrix P:

1Y T n

